    "title": "Using Imported C Macros in Swift"
  },
  "primaryContentSections": [
    {
      "content": [
        {
          "anchor": "Overview",
          "level": 2,
          "text": "Overview",
          "type": "heading"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "text": "Swift automatically imports simple, constant-like macros, declared with the ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "code": "#define",
              "type": "codeVoice"
            },
            {
              "text": " ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": "directive, as global constants. Macros are imported when they use literals for string,",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": " ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": "floating-point, or integer values, or use operators like ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "code": "+",
              "type": "codeVoice"
            },
            {
              "text": ", ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "code": "-",
              "type": "codeVoice"
            },
            {
              "text": ", ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "code": ">",
              "type": "codeVoice"
            },
            {
              "text": ", and ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "code": "==",
              "type": "codeVoice"
            },
            {
              "text": " ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": "between literals or previously defined macros. This example defines some simple macros",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": " ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": "in a C header:",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "code": [
            "#define FADE_ANIMATION_DURATION 0.35",
            "#define VERSION_STRING \"2.2.10.0a\"",
            "#define MAX_RESOLUTION 1268",
            "",
            "#define HALF_RESOLUTION (MAX_RESOLUTION / 2)",
            "#define IS_HIGH_RES (MAX_RESOLUTION > 1024)"
          ],
          "syntax": "occ",
          "type": "codeListing"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "text": "When imported into Swift, the macros in the above example are equivalent to these",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": " ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": "constant declarations:",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "code": [
            "let FADE_ANIMATION_DURATION = 0.35",
            "let VERSION_STRING = \"2.2.10.0a\"",
            "let MAX_RESOLUTION = 1268",
            "",
            "let HALF_RESOLUTION = 634",
            "let IS_HIGH_RES = true"
          ],
          "syntax": "swift",
          "type": "codeListing"
        },
        {
          "anchor": "Use-Functions-and-Generics-Instead-of-Complex-Macros",
          "level": 3,
          "text": "Use Functions and Generics Instead of Complex Macros",
          "type": "heading"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "text": "C macros that are more complex than simple constant definitions have no counterpart",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": " ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": "in Swift. You use complex macros in C and Objective-C to avoid type-checking constraints",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": " ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": "or to avoid retyping large amounts of boilerplate code. However, macros can make",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": " ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": "debugging and refactoring difficult. In Swift, you can use functions and generics",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": " ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": "to achieve the same results without any compromises.",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        }
      ],
      "kind": "content"
    }
  ],
